4/22/2019

Introduction

Climate change and science has been an issue for discussion and debate for at least the last decade. Climate data collection is currently being collected for areas all over the world. Policy decisions are based on the most recent analysis conducted on data extracted from huge online repositories of this data. Due to the inherent growth in the electronic production and storage of information, there is often a feeling of “information overload” or inundation when facing the process of quantitative decision making.

The ability to synthesize large data sets using visualizations is a skill that all data scientists should have. In addition to this data, scientists are called upon to present data syntheses and develop questions or ideas based on their data exploration.

Objective

The objective of this laboratory is to survey the available data, plan, design, and create an information dashboard/presentation that not only explores the data but also develops questions based on that data exploration. To accomplish this task, the following process needs to be completed:

  • Identify what information interests you about climate change.
  • Find, collect, organize, and summarize the data necessary to create your data exploration plan.
  • Design and create the most appropriate visualizations to explore the data and present that information. (no less than 5)
  • Organize the layout of those visualizations into a dashboard in a way that shows your path of data exploration.
  • Develop four questions or ideas about climate change from your visualizations.

Data and Research Background

Data 1 : Northern Hemisphere Sea Ice Extent (1979 - 2019)
Data 2 : Northern Hemisphere Ocean Temperature Anomalies (1979 - 2019)

National Center For Environmental Information https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/

Both the level/amount of sea ice and the atmospheric temperature anomalies are quite important factors of climate change especially global warming. I specifically use these two types of data, two seasons from each year, four compact data sets in total.

  • February Sea Ice Data
  • August Sea Ice Data
  • February Temperature Anomalies Data
  • August Temperature Anomalies Data

Analysis & Visualization 1

I will perform visualizations and analyses in 3 parts; (1). Sea Ice data, (2). Temperature Anomalies data, and (3). Relationships between them.

Relationship between Se Ice Extent & Ocean Temperature Anomalies 1

Now, I would like to check if there exists any interesting relationship between two data set types. It is kind of intuitive to predict that when the ocean temperature anomalies increases the sea ice level decreases, which is a principle definition of global warming.

## [1] -0.8155506

Relationship between Se Ice Extent & Ocean Temperature Anomalies 2

The Pearson correlation test result indicates that there exists a slightly strong negative correlation between sea ice level and temperature anomalies.

Relationship between Se Ice Extent & Ocean Temperature Anomalies 3

Let’s visualize the correlation with scatter plot.

Relationship between Se Ice Extent & Ocean Temperature Anomalies 4

From this scatter plot, we observe a nice linear correlation between two variables.

Let me check their normality by using Shapiro-W test, just to make sure.

## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  comb2$Value.x
## W = 0.95615, p-value = 0.1152

Relationship between Se Ice Extent & Ocean Temperature Anomalies 5

## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  comb2$Value.y
## W = 0.96678, p-value = 0.2694

Their p-values are both greater than the significant level 0.05, therefore,they have normal distributions.

Conclusion

By visualizing the four data sets with line/scatter plots, the following facts were confirmed;

  • The sea ice level in northern hemisphere is decreasing very fast-paced in the last 40 years.
  • The temperature anomalies in northern hemisphere is increasing pretty rapidly in the last 40 years.
  • These two factors have a strong correlation.
